 "cells": [

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# How should we initialize the bandwidth parameter before tuning?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "The initial value of bandwidth greatly affects the optimization efficency. If you choose 'good' initial value, you can save time to calibrate bandwidth. So, the initialization is important for practical use of GWR. Fortunately, you can easily employ the initialization heuristic proposed in Nishi & Asami (2024) with `sgGWR`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "An NVIDIA GPU may be present on this machine, but a CUDA-enabled jaxlib is not installed. Falling back to cpu.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from scipy import interpolate\n",
    "\n",
    "from jax import numpy as jnp\n",
    "from jax import random\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "import sgGWR"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### set up training data\n",
    "\n",
    "First of all, we prepare the same simulation data to the tutorial **Let's start GWR bandwidth calibration with sgGWR!**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1500x500 with 6 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# This spatial coefficient model is inspired by Murakami et al. (2020)\n",
    "def surface(sites, key, sigma, n_grid=30):\n",
    "    s_min = jnp.min(sites, axis=0)\n",
    "    s_max = jnp.max(sites, axis=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "    x = jnp.linspace(s_min[0], s_max[0], num=n_grid)\n",
    "    y = jnp.linspace(s_min[1], s_max[1], num=n_grid)\n",
    "    x_ref, y_ref = np.meshgrid(x, y)\n",
    "    x_ref = x_ref.flatten()\n",
    "    y_ref = y_ref.flatten()\n",
    "    ref = np.stack([x_ref, y_ref]).T\n",
    "\n",
    "    d = np.linalg.norm(ref[:, None] - ref[None], axis=-1)\n",
    "    G = jnp.exp(-d**2)\n",
    "\n",
    "    beta_ref = random.multivariate_normal(key, mean=jnp.ones(len(ref)), cov=sigma**2*G, method=\"svd\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    interp = interpolate.RectBivariateSpline(x, y, beta_ref.reshape(n_grid, n_grid).T, s=0)\n",
    "    beta = interp(sites[:,0], sites[:,1], grid=False)\n",
    "    beta = jnp.array(beta)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return beta\n",
    "\n",
    "def DataGeneration(N, prngkey, sigma2=1.0):\n",
    "    # sites\n",
    "    key, prngkey = random.split(prngkey)\n",
    "    sites = random.normal(key, shape=(N,2))\n",
    "\n",
    "    # kernel\n",
    "    G = jnp.linalg.norm(sites[:,None] - sites[None], axis=-1)\n",
    "    G = jnp.exp(-jnp.square(G))\n",
    "\n",
    "    # coefficients\n",
    "    key, prngkey = random.split(prngkey)\n",
    "    beta0 = surface(sites, key, sigma=0.5)\n",
    "    # beta0 = random.multivariate_normal(key, mean=jnp.ones(N), cov=0.5**2 * G, method=\"svd\")\n",
    "    key, prngkey = random.split(prngkey)\n",
    "    beta1 = surface(sites, key, sigma=2.0)\n",
    "    # beta1 = random.multivariate_normal(key, mean=jnp.ones(N), cov=2.0**2 * G, method=\"svd\")\n",
    "    key, prngkey = random.split(prngkey)\n",
    "    beta2 = surface(sites, key, sigma=0.5)\n",
    "    # beta2 = random.multivariate_normal(key, mean=jnp.ones(N), cov=0.5**2 * G, method=\"svd\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    beta = jnp.stack([beta0, beta1, beta2]).T\n",
    "\n",
    "    # X\n",
    "    key, prngkey = random.split(prngkey)\n",
    "    X = random.normal(key, shape=(N,2))\n",
    "    X = jnp.concatenate([jnp.ones((N,1)), X], axis=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # y\n",
    "    y = beta0 + beta1 * X[:,1] + beta2 * X[:,2]\n",
    "    key, prngkey = random.split(prngkey)\n",
    "    y += sigma2**0.5 * random.normal(key, shape=(N,))\n",
    "\n",
    "    return sites, y, X, beta\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_scatter(x, sites):\n",
    "    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))\n",
    "    for i in range(3):\n",
    "        ax = fig.add_subplot(1,3,i+1)\n",
    "        mappable = ax.scatter(sites[:,0], sites[:,1], c=x[:,i], cmap=plt.cm.RdBu)\n",
    "        ax.set_title(f\"beta {i}\")\n",
    "        ax.set_aspect(\"equal\")\n",
    "        fig.colorbar(mappable)\n",
    "    # fig.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "N = 1000\n",
    "key = random.PRNGKey(123)\n",
    "sites, y, X, beta = DataGeneration(N, key)\n",
    "plot_scatter(beta, sites)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Bad initial value**\n",
    "\n",
    "At first, let us check the performance when we select bad initial value. How this initial value affects the performance?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,

   "source": [
    "kernel = sgGWR.kernels.Exponential(params=[0.001]) # too small initial value\n",
    "model = sgGWR.models.GWR(y=y, X=X, sites=sites, kernel=kernel)\n",
    "optim = sgGWR.optimizers.SGDarmijo(learning_rate0=1.0)\n",
    "\n",
    "loocv_loss = optim.run(model, maxiter=1000, batchsize=100)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"calibrated bandwidth = \", model.kernel.params)"
   ]
  },

    "plt.xlabel(\"LOOCV\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"iteration\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Initialization with Heuristic**\n",
    "\n",
    "Next, we initialize bandwidth with `kernel.init_params` method. To use this method, you need to pass the coordinates of your dataset as `sites` argument.\n",
    "\n",
    "You can also use `idx` argument to specify the index of `sites` which is referred to initialize. If `idx=None`, all data are refered. `idx` is useful when you handle very big data because if you refer all of your data in initialization step, you will spend long time. You don't need to spend long time for initialization because the bandwidth parameter will be optimized later."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json": {
       "model_id": "3b17f63cc200473c8f381199879eebdd",
       "version_major": 2,
       "version_minor": 0
      },
      "text/plain": [
       "  0%|          | 0/1000 [00:00<?, ?it/s]"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "calibrated bandwidth =  [8.72599]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "kernel2 = sgGWR.kernels.Exponential(params=[1.0])\n",
    "kernel2.init_param(sites=sites, idx=None)\n",
    "model2 = sgGWR.models.GWR(y=y, X=X, sites=sites, kernel=kernel2)\n",
    "optim2 = sgGWR.optimizers.SGDarmijo(learning_rate0=1.0)\n",
    "\n",
    "loocv_loss2 = optim2.run(model2, maxiter=1000, batchsize=100)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"calibrated bandwidth = \", model2.kernel.params)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},

    "plt.plot(loocv_loss, label=\"bad initialization\")\n",
    "plt.plot(loocv_loss2, label=\"initialization with heuristics\")\n",

    "plt.ylabel(\"iteration\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If you select bad initial value, it will cause to fail optimization and raise numerical errors. Our heuristic is to avoid such bad values automatically."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "At the end of this tutorial, let us compare estimated coefficient. When the initial value is bad, the estimated coefficients are far from the true values."
   ]
